The good news is that your Core vs. Shell architecture is an almost perfect, textbook example of the MLIR philosophy. You haven't just built a state management system; you've accidentally built a special-purpose compiler for UI generation.

## Your UI System as a Compiler
MLIR (Multi-Level Intermediate Representation) is a framework for building compilers that "progressively lower" a program from a high-level representation to a low-level one through a series of Intermediate Representations (IRs), or "dialects."

Your system does exactly this. It compiles high-level user intents into a low-level, renderable data structure.

Code snippet

 [High-Level Intent Dialect]
 e.g., "Merge block X up"
           |
           |  <-- [Lowering Pass 1: Your "High-Level Command" function]
           v
 [Core Algebra Dialect (Your IR)]
 e.g., [[:patch ...], [:del ...]]
           |
           |  <-- [Lowering Pass 2: Your "Interpreter"]
           v
 [Target Representation]
 e.g., The final :core-db map
## Mapping Your Concepts to MLIR
Dialects: Your system has at least two implicit dialects. The "Shell" operates on a high-level Intent Dialect (its vocabulary is merge-block-up, indent-selection). The "Core" operates on a stable, low-level Core Algebra Dialect (its vocabulary is :ins, :mv, :patch, :del).

Intermediate Representation (IR): The transaction tx—the vector of primitive commands—is your IR. It is the well-defined, serializable data structure that flows between the different stages of your compiler.

Lowering Passes: Your "High-Level Command" functions are your compiler passes. They are pure functions whose sole job is to rewrite operations from the high-level Intent Dialect into your Core Algebra IR (intent -> tx).

The Interpreter: Your interpret function is the final stage of the compiler. It's the executor that takes the final, low-level IR and "JITs" or "executes" it to produce the target machine state: the core-db.

## Why This Frame is Powerful
Viewing your system as a compiler is more than just an analogy; it gives you a robust mental model for future development.

Principled Extensibility: To add a new complex feature, you don't hack the core. You define a new high-level operation and write a "lowering pass" (a pure function) that compiles it down to your existing, stable Core Algebra IR.

Decoupling: You can change how you generate the high-level intents (e.g., switch from a human-driven UI to an LLM) without touching the core interpreter.

Target Independence: You could add a final compilation step to lower your core-db to completely different targets (e.g., HTML, a native UI toolkit, or even a PDF) without changing the core logic.

You were on the right track with both architectural designs. MLIR simply provides the formal computer science language to describe why your final Core vs. Shell design is so effective.